PREFACE

"How to survive the Michigan Winter?" As a southerner who just moved to Michigan, I asked my friend. And he answered, "Canada Goose!" The story of Buydar began with a conversation with my friend. What he meant was actually the brand Canada Goose which was known for its good quality coats and outrageous price. I didn't really make it to buy that tag to wear on, but it made me think: we have designed so many good products and services, what if people cannot afford it?
Later, I realized this was a critical information issue. The fact is there are good affordable alternatives in the market, but people dont know how to get this information, let alone how to make sense of the information. More often than not, both process takes forever for them. They deserve better support in

Buydar, a mobile app which allows users to easily search products they see in brick-and-mortar stores, helps with purchase decision-making through price comparison and user reviews, and enhances shopping efficiency via mobile payment and self-checkout. Also, Buydar meets small retailers needs by digitizing offline shopping. The shopping data collected empowers them to perform precision marketing, inventory optimization and cost reduction.

 

Buydar is an example of my exploration in future retail experience design. In the future, e-commerce and brick-and-mortar stores are no longer binary. The boundary would be ambiguous. Customer, product and environment are going to mingle and create new value together. And technologies like IoT, AI, AR, etc. provide ample opportunities to do so.

Individual Project 2017: UX Designer, Product Strategist, Choice Architect

RESEARCH HIGHLIGHT

Design is pretty much about understanding problems. To define the problem of shopping in brick and mortar stores, I hit the road and interviewed some users and stakeholders. Personas then were created.
Story Mapping is a structured step-by-step analysis of the users tasks. By taking personas into the narrative flow, I was able to capture variation of the tasks and flesh out edge cases. The pain points were found mainly in four core tasks, where there were design opportunities.
As I dived deep into the project, I realized another key stakeholder: small-sized retailers who want to attract more customers but lack the capability to collect data and analyze it to support their marketing strategies and operations. Without taking them into account, the design solution may not be realistic. Then a holistic view of the levels of needs of retail customers and small-sized retailers emerged.

FINAL DESIGN

Digitizing the products in brick-and-mortar stores is the highlight of the solution. RFID tags are attached to the products as unique identification. When held within proximity (eg, 10 inches) with the product, the smart phone with RFID reader can access the product information and search price and reviews. At the same time, the data related to users' shopping behavior is also collected.
Trending Deals
Map View
Navigation

When browsing at the store and interested in a product, the user could press Start Radar. Then Buydar will show the products close to the user sorted by distance.

Then the user could view the product details and compare attributes to make a purchase decision. But how to design the interface to support this process? The NUDGES principles for choice architecture (Thaler et al., 2014) helped me a lot to think through some small details which are impactful for users experience. These principles are: iNcentives, Understanding mapping, Default, Giving feedback, Expecting errors and Structuring complex choices.

If the users decide to buy something, they could add it to cart and quickly pay with the phone. Then they can jump the lines and take the product home, as long as they carry the phone used for payment to pass through the exit with RFID reader embeded.

A good service must take into account the whole user journey, even if the user has left the store. With Buydar, The user will no longer need to look for the paper receipts in the drawers. Managing orders and requesting after-sale service becomes easy and efficient. Though the details of "Contact Seller" feature would depend on the capacity of the retailer.

The product recognition scheme is one of the core design decisions that were made. There were multiple ways to develop my initial idea of mingling offline and online: RFID tag, bar code, camera  identification, etc.. I selected several alternatives and used Question-Option-Criteria method to make my decision.

WHY RFID

I chose RFID mainly because of
  1. Time-saving. Because the APP is used in the retail store when the user is shopping, anything costs too much time or requires much attention or complex actions would interrupt the flow and discourage the user to use the product. 
  2. Reliability/stability. Also, the environment where the mobile APP is used can be various and complex in this case. So reliability/stability is another key factor.
  3. Potential in the future. The solution is based on the trend of Internet of Things in the near future when RFID tags are very likely to be more widely used. Even though the RFID solution requires technological infrastructure, it significantly helps user to make shopping decisions efficiently and stably. It has much potential impact in the near future.
The greatest thing I learned is considering only only the goals and needs, but also the context, contingency and exception. As the users browse in the store and want to search new products around them, do they need to refresh the "Radar" manually each time or it would automatically update? To answer this question, there's a trade-off between technological automation and the user's control over the technology to consider. And both technology and human make mistakes.
 
If I give up the automation, users would spare much effort to retrieve information for each product, which would disturb the natural shopping flow and probably discourage the user to use the app anymore. If I let the product detail page automatically updating as they user walk from product to product, there'er many questions to ask. What if the product recognition goes wrong and it shows another product's page? How does the user know its wrong if there is no image to compare or other clues? How to correct it? When the user need to pick one product from a series of pictures of products around, what if the user picked the wrong one? What if the RFID tag doesn't work or there's even no RFID reader in the user's phone?

CONTEXT, CONTINGENCY, EXCEPTION

At the beginning I designed the automatically refreshing radar feature so that the user didnt have to manually refresh as they walk to different products. And the user could use voice to retrieve information. This seemed applaudable for it reduced the required cognitive resources and simplified users actions. However, in the tests, the users felt lost and confused when the app was beyond their control. The user may still engage in a products page when walking away from it to another, and it's hard to determine whether the user is still viewing the page. Constantly turning on the RFID sensor could also consume much power. The speech control could be unstable in the (loud) store context.
 
By taking into account these contexts and constraints, I removed the speech control feature and refined the product.

The app shows several images of products around (so that they can see which is the one they want). By default, the nearest one occupies the top spot and others are sorted by distance (so that in most cases the user easily get access to the nearest product).

If the users find the right product doesn't show up, they could refresh the "Radar" or transfer to "Scan Bar Code"

The user need to simply push a Refresh Rdar button to let the app recognize a new product; or they could just go back to previous page pick another product if they find it's not what they want.

"Scan Bar Code" is an alternative approach to let the app recognize a product, when the RFID technology goes wrong. If the user's phone doesn't have a RFID reader, this would replace the RFID "Radar" approach.

Thaler, R. H., Sunstein, C. R., & Balz, J. P. (2014). Choice architecture.

IMPACT

While customers could easily search products on different websites and make purchase decisions by comparing products prices and functionalities, reading reviews or even tracking price history, shopping in brick-and-mortar stores is time-consuming and its hard for customers to see how the products work in the long term. They need support in purchase decision making and shooping efficiency.
 
Meanwhile, as e-commerce services become more and more popular, physical retail stores are faced with challenges, especially for those middle and small-sized enterprises. They are facing sales dropping and left behind in the wave of business intelligence. And they lack the capability to collect data and analyze it and make it support their marketing strategies and operations.
Buydar focuses on the future retail experience. The technology of Internet of Things actually has the potential to connect people and merchandises in the physical world and use data to support their experience. On the users side, they could find better products with lower price and make purchase decisions more easily and faster. On the retailers side, the data collected in the retail shopping could be used to anticipate users needs, optimize inventory, support precise marketing. Labor costs could be reduced by mobile payment and self-checkout. Thus retailers can spare more effort on branding and quality of products and services. Without the Buydar, they may not have the capacity to do so, especially for small and middle-sized enterprises. Buydar has the potential to make contribution to the societys economic efficiency.
